Phase 1 should be a pure preparatory refactor: extract validation from mutation, name the row fields, and keep `acceptRow()` returning `boolean` with identical pass/fail behavior and side effects. The review boundary is: existing green tests stay green without changing their assertions.

A tight phase-1 shape is:

```ts
type RawRow = [string, string, string, string];

type CandidateRow = {
  id: string;
  kind: string;
  scoreText: string;
  status: string;
};

function hasFourFields(row: string[]): row is RawRow {
  return row.length === 4;
}

function toCandidateRow(row: RawRow): CandidateRow {
  const [id, kind, scoreText, status] = row;
  return { id, kind, scoreText, status };
}

function isValidCandidateRow(row: CandidateRow): boolean {
  return row.id !== ""
    && (row.kind === "person" || row.kind === "company")
    && /^\d+$/.test(row.scoreText)
    && (row.status === "active" || row.status === "inactive");
}

export function acceptRow(row: string[]): boolean {
  if (!hasFourFields(row)) {
    return false;
  }

  const candidate = toCandidateRow(row);
  if (!isValidCandidateRow(candidate)) {
    return false;
  }

  acceptedRows.push({
    id: candidate.id,
    kind: candidate.kind,
    score: Number(candidate.scoreText),
    status: candidate.status,
  });

  return true;
}
```

That is enough refactoring because it exposes validation as a separate unit and removes nested conditionals without altering observable behavior.

Phase 2 should change the contract deliberately: return a typed rejection reason, make data meaning explicit in the types, and keep mutation only on accepted input. The validation function becomes the main seam.

```ts
type RowKind = "person" | "company";
type RowStatus = "active" | "inactive";

type AcceptanceResult =
  | { accepted: true }
  | {
      accepted: false;
      reason: "field-count" | "missing-id" | "kind" | "score" | "status";
    };

type ParsedRow = {
  id: string;
  kind: RowKind;
  score: number;
  status: RowStatus;
};

type CandidateRow = {
  id: string;
  kind: string;
  scoreText: string;
  status: string;
};

function validateRow(row: string[]): AcceptanceResult {
  if (!hasFourFields(row)) {
    return { accepted: false, reason: "field-count" };
  }

  const candidate = toCandidateRow(row);

  if (candidate.id === "") {
    return { accepted: false, reason: "missing-id" };
  }

  if (candidate.kind !== "person" && candidate.kind !== "company") {
    return { accepted: false, reason: "kind" };
  }

  if (!/^\d+$/.test(candidate.scoreText)) {
    return { accepted: false, reason: "score" };
  }

  if (candidate.status !== "active" && candidate.status !== "inactive") {
    return { accepted: false, reason: "status" };
  }

  return { accepted: true };
}

function parseAcceptedRow(row: [string, string, string, string]): ParsedRow {
  const [id, kind, scoreText, status] = row;
  return {
    id,
    kind: kind as RowKind,
    score: Number(scoreText),
    status: status as RowStatus,
  };
}

export function acceptRow(row: string[]): AcceptanceResult {
  const result = validateRow(row);
  if (!result.accepted) {
    return result;
  }

  const parsed = parseAcceptedRow(row as [string, string, string, string]);
  acceptedRows.push(parsed);
  return { accepted: true };
}
```

Test split:

1. Phase 1: keep current tests unchanged; optionally add helper-level characterization tests only if your test style allows structural coverage without changing observable expectations.
2. Phase 2: update acceptance assertions to expect `{ accepted: true }` and add one rejection test each for `field-count`, `missing-id`, `kind`, `score`, and `status`.

Minimal rejection matrix:

- `[]` or 3/5 fields -> `field-count`
- `["", "person", "10", "active"]` -> `missing-id`
- `["1", "robot", "10", "active"]` -> `kind`
- `["1", "person", "10x", "active"]` -> `score`
- `["1", "person", "10", "pending"]` -> `status`

This keeps the two intents clean: first a preparatory refactor that only exposes the seam, then the behavior change that introduces typed outcomes and exhaustive rejection tests.
